-Okay, calm down.
-(knocking on door)

60
00:03:18,406 --> 00:03:20,366
MARGE:
Homer, can you get the door?

61
00:03:20,450 --> 00:03:21,743
It's my sisters.

62
00:03:21,826 --> 00:03:22,911
(quavering)

63
00:03:22,994 --> 00:03:24,412
Homer. Be nice.

64
00:03:24,495 --> 00:03:26,247
Okay, I will, I will.

65
00:03:26,331 --> 00:03:28,416
(grumbling)
Coming over here...

66
00:03:28,499 --> 00:03:31,461
Patty, Thelma,
what a pleasant surprise!

67
00:03:31,544 --> 00:03:34,380
What do you know--
he's wearing pants.

68
00:03:34,464 --> 00:03:35,590
I owe you a lunch.

69
00:03:35,673 --> 00:03:37,926
PATTY:
Ugly.

70
00:03:38,009 --> 00:03:39,427
Ugly.

71
00:03:39,510 --> 00:03:40,637
Butch.

72
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:42,096
What's the matter?

73
00:03:42,180 --> 00:03:44,307
Can't you find a
hairstyle you like?

74
00:03:44,390 --> 00:03:45,642
Hold the phone.

75
00:03:45,725 --> 00:03:47,352
That's the one for me.

76
00:03:47,435 --> 00:03:48,895
Ed Asner?

77
00:03:48,978 --> 00:03:50,897
No, next to him.

78
00:03:50,980 --> 00:03:52,774
Mary Tyler Moore.

79
00:03:52,857 --> 00:03:54,484
(all)
Mm.

80
00:03:54,567 --> 00:03:57,237
Expiration date, June, 1989...

81
00:03:57,320 --> 00:04:00,907
Uh, 2012. Yeah.

82
00:04:00,990 --> 00:04:03,451
Homer, are you ordering junk
off the TV again?

83
00:04:03,534 --> 00:04:05,536
-Shh! They'll hear you.
-(power saw whirring)

84
00:04:05,620 --> 00:04:08,164
Oh, who's using
the power tools?

85
00:04:08,248 --> 00:04:10,583
-I don't know. Some guy, I guess.
-Mmm.

86
00:04:10,667 --> 00:04:12,502
Well, we're going
to the beauty parlor.

87
00:04:12,585 --> 00:04:14,587
Maybe you should do something
with the kids while I'm gone.

88
00:04:14,671 --> 00:04:16,881
Oh, sure, great idea.

89
00:04:16,965 --> 00:04:18,299
I'd love to.

90
00:04:18,383 --> 00:04:20,343
-D'oh! Did you hear that?
-Yes.

91
00:04:20,426 --> 00:04:21,970
-How much?
-Everything.

92
00:04:22,053 --> 00:04:23,304
What's the quickest,
cheapest, easiest way

93
00:04:23,388 --> 00:04:24,597
to do something with you?

94
00:04:24,681 --> 00:04:26,474
Take us to the video store?

95
00:04:26,557 --> 00:04:28,309
Anything for my little girl.

96
00:04:31,479 --> 00:04:32,939
Bart!

97
00:04:33,022 --> 00:04:35,650
You can't weld
with such a little flame.

98
00:04:35,733 --> 00:04:37,235
Stupid kid.

99
00:04:44,200 --> 00:04:46,703
Ooh! McBain.

100
00:04:46,786 --> 00:04:48,997
Mm-mm-mm.

101
00:04:49,080 --> 00:04:51,666
Hey, McBain, you keep eating
them hot links,

102
00:04:51,749 --> 00:04:53,251
you never going to make it
to a pension.

103
00:04:53,334 --> 00:04:55,628
Come on,
live a little, Skowie.

104
00:04:55,712 --> 00:04:57,088
No, thank you.
I got me a future, partnah.

105
00:04:57,171 --> 00:04:59,090
I'm two days away from
retirement

106
00:04:59,173 --> 00:05:01,134
My daughter's graduating
from college.

107
00:05:01,217 --> 00:05:02,844
Little Suzie is growing up.

108
00:05:02,927 --> 00:05:04,804
And as soon as we nail Mendoza,

109
00:05:04,887 --> 00:05:06,556
my old lady and I

110
00:05:06,639 --> 00:05:08,558
are gonna sail around the world
like we always wanted.

111
00:05:08,641 --> 00:05:11,019
We just christened a boat.

112
00:05:11,102 --> 00:05:14,272
Oh, yes, sir, everything
is going to be just perf...

113
00:05:14,355 --> 00:05:16,482
(gunshots)

114
00:05:16,566 --> 00:05:18,276
Ahhh!

115
00:05:21,571 --> 00:05:22,572
(gunshots)

116
00:05:27,285 --> 00:05:29,871
Damn, damn, damn.

117
00:05:29,954 --> 00:05:31,831
-McBain...
-Yes?

118
00:05:31,914 --> 00:05:33,333
I'm not going to make it.

119
00:05:33,416 --> 00:05:34,792
-Oh, stop talking crazy.
-No, no, no.

120
00:05:34,876 --> 00:05:37,295
Just do one thing for me.

121
00:05:37,378 --> 00:05:40,006
Get... Mendoza.

122
00:05:43,968 --> 00:05:49,766
Mendoza!

123
00:05:49,849 --> 00:05:50,975
You want to rent it, sir?

124
00:05:51,059 --> 00:05:52,477
Why?

125
00:05:52,560 --> 00:05:54,062
I just saw the best part.
(chuckles)

126
00:05:56,397 --> 00:06:00,026
Ooh! <i>Death By Knockout,</i>
<i>Blood on the Ice...</i>

127
00:06:00,109 --> 00:06:01,319
Ho, ho!

128
00:06:01,402 --> 00:06:04,447
<i>Football's Greatest Injuries.</i>

129
00:06:04,530 --> 00:06:07,033
-Lisa, we're going.
-But, Dad, I can't find

130
00:06:07,116 --> 00:06:09,369
<i>Happy Little Elves</i>
<i>in Tinkly Winkly Town.</i>

131
00:06:09,452 --> 00:06:11,913
Just grab something!
All these movies are great.

132
00:06:13,873 --> 00:06:15,208
Look at this.

133
00:06:15,291 --> 00:06:18,461
"Test your F.Q."--
Fatherhood Quotient.

134
00:06:18,544 --> 00:06:20,755
Maybe you should try it
on Homer.

135
00:06:20,838 --> 00:06:22,006
He'll fail it.

136
00:06:22,090 --> 00:06:23,841
Uh-huh, in a second.

137
00:06:23,925 --> 00:06:25,385
Well,
I don't know.

138
00:06:25,468 --> 00:06:28,805
Oh, now Henry Winkler--
there's a father.

139
00:06:28,888 --> 00:06:31,432
Listen to what he told
a close friend.

140
00:06:31,516 --> 00:06:34,268
"I don't always keep my cool
like The Fonz,

141
00:06:34,352 --> 00:06:36,270
"but my love for my kids

142
00:06:36,354 --> 00:06:39,649
-has given me plenty of happy days."
-Mmm.

143
00:06:39,732 --> 00:06:42,360
ANNOUNCER: <i>They called him</i>
<i>"The Galloping Gazelle."</i>

144
00:06:42,443 --> 00:06:45,947
<i>His habitat: The frozen tundra</i>
<i>of Soldier Field.</i>

145
00:06:46,030 --> 00:06:47,865
<i>For six seasons</i>
<i>and two Pro Bowls,</i>

146
00:06:47,949 --> 00:06:49,951
<i>he grazed on the tasty</i>
<i>green turf of the end zone,</i>

147
00:06:50,034 --> 00:06:52,703
<i>until one fateful Sunday</i>
<i>in November,</i>

148
00:06:52,787 --> 00:06:55,832
<i>when the Gazelle was</i>
<i>stopped in his tracks</i>

149
00:06:55,915 --> 00:06:58,418
<i>by a big cat named</i>
<i>Wayne Suschevski.</i>

150
00:06:58,501 --> 00:07:01,963
-(door slams)
-Homey, we're back.

151
00:07:02,046 --> 00:07:05,299
-(laughing)
-Don't mind that clod, Patty.

152
00:07:05,383 --> 00:07:07,677
You could turn the world on
with your smile.

153
00:07:07,760 --> 00:07:10,346
Homer, could you turn off
the TV?

154
00:07:10,430 --> 00:07:12,014
There's a little test
I want you to take.

155
00:07:12,098 --> 00:07:13,933
<i>-(bones cracking on TV)</i>
-Oh, great.

156
00:07:14,016 --> 00:07:15,852
You made me miss Joe Theisman.

157
00:07:15,935 --> 00:07:19,313
This is from the National
Fatherhood Institute.

158
00:07:19,397 --> 00:07:22,567
It evaluates your knowledge
of your son and rates you as a father.

159
00:07:22,650 --> 00:07:23,901
Oh, Marge.

160
00:07:23,985 --> 00:07:25,403
Question one:

161
00:07:25,486 --> 00:07:27,196
"Name one of
your child's friends."

162
00:07:27,280 --> 00:07:29,782
Uh, let's see...
Bart's friends..

163
00:07:29,866 --> 00:07:32,702
Well, there's the fat kid
with the thing.

164
00:07:32,785 --> 00:07:34,954
The little wiener who's always
got his hands in his pockets.

165
00:07:35,037 --> 00:07:37,373
They want a name, Homer,
not a vague description.

166
00:07:37,457 --> 00:07:39,167
Okay... Hank?

167
00:07:39,250 --> 00:07:40,501
Hank? Hank who?

168
00:07:40,585 --> 00:07:41,711
Hank... Jones.

169
00:07:41,794 --> 00:07:43,546
Homer, you made that up.

170
00:07:43,629 --> 00:07:44,839
Question two:

171
00:07:44,922 --> 00:07:46,507
"Who is your son's hero?"

172
00:07:46,591 --> 00:07:47,550
Steve McQueen.

173
00:07:47,633 --> 00:07:49,385
That's your hero.

174
00:07:49,469 --> 00:07:50,595
"Name another Dad

175
00:07:50,678 --> 00:07:52,013
you talk to
about parenting."

176
00:07:52,096 --> 00:07:54,265
-Next.
-"What are your son's hobbies?"

177
00:07:54,348 --> 00:07:55,766
Well, he's always chewing on
that phone cord.

178
00:07:55,850 --> 00:07:57,560
He hasn't done that
since he was two.

179
00:07:57,643 --> 00:07:59,896
-Then he has no hobbies.
-Oh, really?

180
00:07:59,979 --> 00:08:02,482
Well, maybe you should go out
to the garage and see.

181
00:08:05,276 --> 00:08:07,612
-Bart. Bart!
-What?

182
00:08:07,695 --> 00:08:09,030
You don't have any hobbies,
do you, boy?

183
00:08:09,113 --> 00:08:10,072
No, not really.

184
00:08:10,156 --> 00:08:11,866
Well, that's what I...

185
00:08:11,949 --> 00:08:12,950
Wait a minute,
What are you doing?

186
00:08:13,034 --> 00:08:14,619
Building a Soap Box Derby racer.

187
00:08:14,702 --> 00:08:15,620
(groans)

188
00:08:15,703 --> 00:08:16,913
That's a hobby.

189
00:08:16,996 --> 00:08:18,456
Hey, so it is.

190
00:08:18,539 --> 00:08:19,916
Oh, my God.

191
00:08:19,999 --> 00:08:21,792
I don't know jack about my boy.

192
00:08:21,876 --> 00:08:23,211
(sobbing)

193
00:08:23,294 --> 00:08:25,379
I'm a bad father.

194
00:08:25,463 --> 00:08:26,964
You're also fat.

195
00:08:27,048 --> 00:08:29,675
I'm also fat!

196
00:08:35,681 --> 00:08:38,309
MAN (on phone): <i>National</i>
<i>Fatherhood Institute. Please hold.</i>

197
00:08:38,392 --> 00:08:41,687
<i>♪ And the cat's in the cradle</i>
<i>and the silver spoon ♪</i>

198
00:08:41,771 --> 00:08:44,607
<i>♪ Little Boy Blue</i>
<i>and the Man on the Moon ♪</i>

199
00:08:44,690 --> 00:08:46,359
<i>♪ When you comin' home, Dad? ♪</i>

200
00:08:46,442 --> 00:08:48,236
<i>♪ I don't know when... ♪</i>

201
00:08:48,319 --> 00:08:50,947
National Fatherhood Institute.
Dave speaking.

202
00:08:51,030 --> 00:08:53,115
<i>I'm Homer Simpson.</i>
<i>I just took your test.</i>

203
00:08:53,199 --> 00:08:55,618
-I got a zero.
-Good Lord! A zero?

204
00:08:55,701 --> 00:08:58,371
Lana, cancel my 1:00.
Mr. Simpson, we'll send

205
00:08:58,454 --> 00:09:00,581
<i>a wood-paneled station wagon</i>
<i>over for you immediately.</i>

206
00:09:00,665 --> 00:09:03,251
Hey, Bart, where did
you get the lumber?

207
00:09:03,334 --> 00:09:06,796
Well, as three-time Soap Box
Derby champ Ronnie Beck says,

208
00:09:06,879 --> 00:09:09,131
"Poorly guarded construction
sites are a gold mine."

209
00:09:09,215 --> 00:09:10,883
A conventional design.

210
00:09:10,967 --> 00:09:13,261
Oh, yeah? Are you building
a racer, Martin?

211
00:09:13,344 --> 00:09:15,054
In between some other projects.

212
00:09:15,137 --> 00:09:16,889
Well, gentlemen,
if you'll excuse me,

213
00:09:16,973 --> 00:09:18,391
I've booked some time
at the wind tunnel.

214
00:09:23,729 --> 00:09:25,648
Good-bye, son.

215
00:09:25,731 --> 00:09:28,234
Hey, Bart, I think they're finally
hauling your dad away.

216
00:09:28,317 --> 00:09:29,569
Maybe it's for the best.

217
00:09:32,488 --> 00:09:34,240
<i>♪ Oh, you are ♪</i>

218
00:09:34,323 --> 00:09:36,242
<i>♪ One in a million... ♪</i>

219
00:09:38,119 --> 00:09:41,163
For starters, Mr. Simpson,
why don't you take

220
00:09:41,247 --> 00:09:43,916
this complimentary copy of <i>Fatherhood</i>
by Bill Cosby.

221
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:47,128
If he's as smart
as he is funny, I'm sold.

222
00:09:47,211 --> 00:09:49,130
Mr. Simpson,
if you want to be a good father,

223
00:09:49,213 --> 00:09:51,299
you have to spend time
with your son.

224
00:09:51,382 --> 00:09:52,967
That's easy for you to say,

225
00:09:53,050 --> 00:09:56,053
you preachy, egg-headed
institute guy.

226
00:09:56,137 --> 00:09:57,805
How much do you see your son?

227
00:09:57,888 --> 00:09:59,557
Why don't you ask him
yourself.

228
00:09:59,640 --> 00:10:01,809
-Homer, meet Dave, Jr.
-Huh?

229
00:10:01,892 --> 00:10:03,686
How's your research coming, son?

230
00:10:03,769 --> 00:10:05,646
I think we're near
a breakthrough.

231
00:10:05,730 --> 00:10:07,064
-Good work.
-Thanks, Dad.

232
00:10:07,148 --> 00:10:08,899
Oh, how I envy you.

233
00:10:08,983 --> 00:10:10,651
Homer, that easy back
and forther you witnessed

234
00:10:10,735 --> 00:10:11,652
didn't happen overnight.

235
00:10:11,736 --> 00:10:13,321
It took years of effort.

236
00:10:13,404 --> 00:10:15,615
I've never been afraid
of a little hard work.

237
00:10:15,698 --> 00:10:17,450
That's the spirit,
Mr. Simpson.

238
00:10:17,533 --> 00:10:20,453
Now, step one is to find an activity
the two of you can share.

239
00:10:20,536 --> 00:10:21,579
Does the boy
have any interests?

240
00:10:21,662 --> 00:10:23,122
-What boy?
-Your son.

241
00:10:23,205 --> 00:10:25,583
Find something he likes to do
and share in it.

242
00:10:25,666 --> 00:10:28,711
Well, he is building
a Soap Box Derby racer!

243
00:10:28,794 --> 00:10:31,213
-Oh, that would be perfect.
-(klaxon blaring)

244
00:10:31,297 --> 00:10:34,050
Dear God! Not again!

245
00:10:34,133 --> 00:10:37,803
Bart, I'm going to help you
build that racer.

246
00:10:37,887 --> 00:10:39,597
Thanks,
but I'm almost done.

247
00:10:39,680 --> 00:10:41,349
Why don't you get back
on the couch and watch TV.

248
00:10:41,432 --> 00:10:42,350
Okay.

249
00:10:42,433 --> 00:10:44,393
No! I'm going to do it.

250
00:10:44,477 --> 00:10:47,772
Sorry, Dad, but three-time Soap Box
Derby champion Ronnie Beck

251
00:10:47,855 --> 00:10:49,190
never needed his dad's help.

252
00:10:49,273 --> 00:10:51,108
But you can use me.
I'm good.

253
00:10:51,192 --> 00:10:53,027
I built a lot of things
around the house:

254
00:10:53,110 --> 00:10:56,614
-The spice rack.
-(glass shatters)

255
00:10:56,697 --> 00:10:57,698
The bird feeder.

256
00:10:59,492 --> 00:11:00,409
The Gymboree.

257
00:11:04,330 --> 00:11:06,040
What was that?
Ah, who cares?

258
00:11:06,123 --> 00:11:07,291
Son, please let me help you.

259
00:11:07,375 --> 00:11:09,210
Come on, Dad.
It would be weird.

260
00:11:09,293 --> 00:11:11,337
This isn't working at all.

261
00:11:11,420 --> 00:11:12,338
It's hopeless.

262
00:11:12,421 --> 00:11:13,839
Wait a second.

263
00:11:16,300 --> 00:11:17,968
Hmm.

264
00:11:18,052 --> 00:11:21,097
"Cosby's First Law
of Intergenerational Perversity.

265
00:11:21,180 --> 00:11:23,474
"No matter what you tell
your child to do,

266
00:11:23,557 --> 00:11:24,975
he will always do
the opposite."

267
00:11:25,059 --> 00:11:26,477
Huh?

268
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:28,020
<i>(thinking)</i>
<i>Don't you get it?</i>

269
00:11:28,104 --> 00:11:29,230
<i>You gotta use</i>
<i>reverse psychology.</i>

270
00:11:29,313 --> 00:11:31,148
That sounds too complicated.

271
00:11:31,232 --> 00:11:32,900
<i>Okay, don't use</i>
<i>reverse psychology.</i>

272
00:11:32,983 --> 00:11:34,610
All right, I will.

273
00:11:34,694 --> 00:11:37,196
Son, I don't think
you should let me help you.

274
00:11:37,279 --> 00:11:38,823
Oh, come on, Dad,
if you really want to help,

275
00:11:38,906 --> 00:11:40,282
you can clean these paint
brushes.

276
00:11:40,366 --> 00:11:41,867
Thank you, Bill Cosby.

277
00:11:41,951 --> 00:11:43,661
You've saved the Simpsons.

278
00:11:43,744 --> 00:11:48,082
<i>♪ There he sits</i>
<i>with a pen and a yellow pad ♪</i>

279
00:11:48,165 --> 00:11:50,084
<i>♪ What a handsome lad ♪</i>

280
00:11:50,167 --> 00:11:53,003
<i>♪ That's my boy ♪</i>

281
00:11:53,087 --> 00:11:58,926
<i>♪ B-R-L-F-Q spells</i>
<i>"Mom" and "Dad" ♪</i>

282
00:11:59,009 --> 00:12:00,553
<i>♪ Well, that ain't too bad ♪</i>

283
00:12:00,636 --> 00:12:03,973
<i>♪ 'Cause that's my boy ♪</i>

284
00:12:04,056 --> 00:12:08,310
<i>♪ You can have your TV</i>
<i>and your nightclubs... ♪</i>

285
00:12:11,897 --> 00:12:14,859
You know, Marge,
that Bart of ours is a little miracle--

286
00:12:14,942 --> 00:12:16,986
his winning smile,
his button nose,

287
00:12:17,069 --> 00:12:18,904
his fat, little stomach.

288
00:12:18,988 --> 00:12:20,990
His face alight
with wholesome mischief.

289
00:12:21,073 --> 00:12:23,200
He reminds me of me

290
00:12:23,284 --> 00:12:25,244
before the weight of the world
crushed my spirit.

291
00:12:25,327 --> 00:12:26,746
Hmm, yeah.

292
00:12:26,829 --> 00:12:30,666
(trumpet fanfare)

293
00:12:34,795 --> 00:12:37,006
I like our chances, son.

294
00:12:37,089 --> 00:12:39,550
Ugh! Your father's not
supposed to help build your racer,

295
00:12:39,633 --> 00:12:41,302
but you should at least
consult him about it.

296
00:12:41,385 --> 00:12:43,471
-D'oh!
-You're in heat four.

297
00:12:43,554 --> 00:12:45,973
-Whoa, where's your helmet, son?
-Helmets are for wusses, sir.

298
00:12:46,056 --> 00:12:48,476
No, I don't think I can let you go
without a safety helmet.

299
00:12:48,559 --> 00:12:51,353
This is my son, and if he
doesn't want to wear one,

300
00:12:51,437 --> 00:12:52,438
you can't make him.

301
00:12:52,521 --> 00:12:54,148
Okay, fine.

302
00:12:54,231 --> 00:12:55,399
I want to get out
of here sometime today.

303
00:12:55,483 --> 00:12:57,318
Attention, everyone.

304
00:12:57,401 --> 00:13:00,571
I say to those who question
the value of the space program,

305
00:13:00,654 --> 00:13:02,323
behold!

306
00:13:05,409 --> 00:13:08,120
Ay, caramba!

307
00:13:08,204 --> 00:13:10,080
Hey, you're not supposed
to smoke in the pit area.

308
00:13:10,164 --> 00:13:11,040
Fine.

309
00:13:13,125 --> 00:13:15,586
Hey, Simpson!
Where's your losermobile?

310
00:13:15,669 --> 00:13:18,547
(laughing)
Losermobile. Wait a minute.

311
00:13:18,631 --> 00:13:20,925
Uh, it's over there, Nelson.

312
00:13:21,008 --> 00:13:24,220
Whoa, talk about
your pieces of crap.

313
00:13:24,303 --> 00:13:25,846
You know, Bart,
I don't care who wins

314
00:13:25,930 --> 00:13:27,848
as long as one of us
beats that guy.

315
00:13:27,932 --> 00:13:29,517
Same here.

316
00:13:29,600 --> 00:13:32,853
Careful boys, it took me months
to steal that bumper.

317
00:13:32,937 --> 00:13:34,563
BOY:
Help! Help!

318
00:13:34,647 --> 00:13:35,773
-What was that?
-You didn't hear nothing!

319
00:13:37,441 --> 00:13:39,443
-Are you nervous, son?
-Don't worry, Dad.

320
00:13:39,527 --> 00:13:42,321
As three-time Soap Box Derby
champion Ronnie Beck says:

321
00:13:42,404 --> 00:13:44,323
"Gravity is my co-pilot."

322
00:13:44,406 --> 00:13:46,826
Hey, Boss.
Just in case you need it.

323
00:13:46,909 --> 00:13:49,453
Aw, thanks, guys.

324
00:13:50,955 --> 00:13:52,623
Now get outta here!

325
00:13:52,706 --> 00:13:56,043
Oh, I didn't realize
this hill was so high.

326
00:13:56,126 --> 00:13:57,878
Could I have another--

327
00:13:57,962 --> 00:14:00,089
(Martin screaming)

328
00:14:06,804 --> 00:14:08,138
(screaming)

329
00:14:09,807 --> 00:14:11,267
(crowd cheering)

330
00:14:14,854 --> 00:14:17,898
(crowd cheering)

331
00:14:17,982 --> 00:14:19,608
(laughing)

332
00:14:21,402 --> 00:14:23,863
Deploy, damn you!
Deploy!

333
00:14:25,155 --> 00:14:26,073
(crowd gasping)

334
00:14:27,575 --> 00:14:29,577
(Martin screaming)

335
00:14:32,371 --> 00:14:34,623
It hurts! It hurts!

336
00:14:34,707 --> 00:14:36,292
Owee! Owee! Owee! Ow!

337
00:14:36,375 --> 00:14:37,960
Mm-hmm.

338
00:14:38,043 --> 00:14:39,628
Young man, I'm afraid
this stress fracture

339
00:14:39,712 --> 00:14:42,631
will require you
to be in a cast for six weeks.

340
00:14:42,715 --> 00:14:44,925
But that means
I can't possibly race.

341
00:14:45,009 --> 00:14:46,302
Son, you're lucky
to be alive.

342
00:14:46,385 --> 00:14:47,845
Save your palliative clichés

343
00:14:47,928 --> 00:14:50,097
for the next poor sap,
Doctor.

344
00:14:50,180 --> 00:14:51,807
Is it okay to visit?

345
00:14:51,891 --> 00:14:53,350
(chuckling)
Of course.

346
00:14:53,434 --> 00:14:55,060
Hey, man, cool crash.

347
00:14:55,144 --> 00:14:57,605
-Way to cheat death.
-Thanks, Bart.

348
00:14:57,688 --> 00:14:59,481
You had the best stick
out there, man.

349
00:14:59,565 --> 00:15:01,609
I wish I could
build 'em like you.

350
00:15:01,692 --> 00:15:04,570
That racer transformed me
into the twisted creature

351
00:15:04,653 --> 00:15:06,405
you see before you.

352
00:15:06,488 --> 00:15:08,699
I'll never race again.

353
00:15:08,782 --> 00:15:10,826
If you don't race,
then Nelson will win.

354
00:15:10,910 --> 00:15:14,330
Even if I wanted to,
I'm in no shape to do it.

355
00:15:14,413 --> 00:15:15,789
Unless...

356
00:15:15,873 --> 00:15:18,542
Bart, will you drive my car?

357
00:15:18,626 --> 00:15:20,336
I don't know
if I should do that.

358
00:15:20,419 --> 00:15:22,212
My Dad and I built
our car together,

359
00:15:22,296 --> 00:15:25,090
and if I drove someone else's,
it would kill him.

360
00:15:25,174 --> 00:15:27,301
On the other hand, I'll do it.

361
00:15:27,384 --> 00:15:30,304
Okay, Bart. We've got
a lot of work to do on the car.

362
00:15:30,387 --> 00:15:32,765
So I'm gonna pull you out of school
for the next couple of weeks.

363
00:15:32,848 --> 00:15:35,267
Dad, I don't know
how to say this, but..

364
00:15:35,351 --> 00:15:36,727
I don't want to drive your car.

365
00:15:36,810 --> 00:15:38,646
It's slow, it's ugly.

366
00:15:38,729 --> 00:15:40,648
It handles
like a shopping cart.

367
00:15:40,731 --> 00:15:42,691
Bart, the car has a few bugs
in it, I admit that,

368
00:15:42,775 --> 00:15:44,526
but we're Team Simpson.

369
00:15:44,610 --> 00:15:48,030
Dad, I love you,
but you taught me to win.

370
00:15:48,113 --> 00:15:49,156
When did I ever
teach you that?

371
00:15:49,239 --> 00:15:50,824
Well, I picked it up somewhere.

372
00:15:50,908 --> 00:15:52,952
And if I drive Martin's car,
I can win.

373
00:15:53,035 --> 00:15:54,161
I'm sorry, but...

374
00:15:54,244 --> 00:15:56,038
No, go ahead, leave me.

375
00:15:56,121 --> 00:15:58,040
-Dad...
-Go on. Go on and win.

376
00:15:58,123 --> 00:16:00,000
No, go on and win
without your Dad.

377
00:16:00,084 --> 00:16:02,711
I'll just sit here
in Li'l Lightnin',

378
00:16:02,795 --> 00:16:04,880
which the Simpsons built,

379
00:16:04,964 --> 00:16:06,966
and remember that
for one brief shining moment,

380
00:16:07,049 --> 00:16:08,926
I had a son.

381
00:16:13,764 --> 00:16:14,890
Ow.

382
00:16:20,521 --> 00:16:21,981
Ohh!

383
00:16:22,064 --> 00:16:24,191
Dad, can you take me
to Dr. Hibbert's office?

384
00:16:24,274 --> 00:16:26,443
-Why? What's wrong?
-Oh, nothing.

385
00:16:26,527 --> 00:16:28,195
I just scheduled a tetanus
booster.

386
00:16:28,278 --> 00:16:29,697
Maybe I'm being
a little anal,

387
00:16:29,780 --> 00:16:31,573
but barefoot season's coming up

388
00:16:31,657 --> 00:16:33,200
and there's a world
of rusty nails out there.

389
00:16:33,283 --> 00:16:34,535
Oh, sure, I'll take you,

390
00:16:34,618 --> 00:16:36,537
wait with you,
worry about you,

391
00:16:36,620 --> 00:16:38,789
and then you'll ride home with
someone who has a faster car.

392
00:16:38,872 --> 00:16:40,874
This is how you get your kicks,
isn't it, Lisa?

393
00:16:40,958 --> 00:16:42,292
Hmm.

394
00:16:44,628 --> 00:16:45,546
D'oh!

395
00:16:48,007 --> 00:16:50,217
Martin, your bone
is healing nicely.

396
00:16:50,300 --> 00:16:51,969
Tell me something
I don't know.

397
00:16:52,052 --> 00:16:53,512
(chuckles)

398
00:16:53,595 --> 00:16:54,888
Dr. Hibbert, Lisa needs a...

399
00:16:54,972 --> 00:16:56,223
You!

400
00:16:56,306 --> 00:16:57,975
Home wrecker!

401
00:16:58,058 --> 00:17:01,478
Mr. Simpson, you have every
right to be angry.

402
00:17:01,562 --> 00:17:03,647
But rest assured,
your son loves you.

403
00:17:03,731 --> 00:17:05,357
-(growls)
-(screams)

404
00:17:05,441 --> 00:17:07,568
(Hibbert laughs)

405
00:17:07,651 --> 00:17:09,570
You certainly gave that boy
the heebie-jeebies.

406
00:17:16,493 --> 00:17:18,370
-Dad, aren't you coming?
-No.

407
00:17:18,454 --> 00:17:21,623
-Now, don't pout.
-I'm not pouting. You are.

408
00:17:21,707 --> 00:17:23,584
Dad, you gotta come.

409
00:17:23,667 --> 00:17:25,627
-I just got your hat out of the fridge.
-Sorry.

410
00:17:25,711 --> 00:17:27,963
Don't you at least
have something to say to Bart?

411
00:17:28,047 --> 00:17:30,507
HOMER:
No. Can't think of a thing.

412
00:17:30,591 --> 00:17:33,510
Homer, I've always said
you were a good father.

413
00:17:33,594 --> 00:17:36,597
I've always defended you
when people put you down.

414
00:17:36,680 --> 00:17:38,932
-That's for sure.
-She ain't lyin'.

415
00:17:39,016 --> 00:17:40,559
But I guess I was wrong.

416
00:17:40,642 --> 00:17:42,686
You are a bad father.

417
00:17:42,770 --> 00:17:43,812
Leave me alone.

418
00:17:48,025 --> 00:17:50,194
(fanfare playing)

419
00:17:50,277 --> 00:17:52,029
TV ANNOUNCER:
<i>Good morning, everybody,</i>

420
00:17:52,112 --> 00:17:54,156
<i>and welcome to an event</i>
<i>that harkens back</i>

421
00:17:54,239 --> 00:17:56,533
<i>to the carefree days</i>
<i>of the Great Depression--</i>

422
00:17:56,617 --> 00:17:58,160
<i>The Soap Box Derby.</i>

423
00:17:58,243 --> 00:18:00,037
<i>In just minutes,</i>

424
00:18:00,120 --> 00:18:03,290
<i>these junior Al Unser, Jrs.</i>
<i>will lock horns.</i>

425
00:18:04,416 --> 00:18:05,709
Huh?

426
00:18:05,793 --> 00:18:07,795
"Name your son's hobbies."

427
00:18:07,878 --> 00:18:09,922
Building a soap box racer.

428
00:18:10,005 --> 00:18:12,216
"Name one
of your child's friends."

429
00:18:12,299 --> 00:18:13,217
Martin.

430
00:18:13,300 --> 00:18:14,802
Martin!

431
00:18:14,885 --> 00:18:16,970
I'll curse that name
till the day I die!

432
00:18:17,054 --> 00:18:18,639
Huh?

433
00:18:18,722 --> 00:18:20,933
"Who is your son's hero?"

434
00:18:21,016 --> 00:18:24,228
Three-time Soap Box Derby
champion, Ronnie Beck.

435
00:18:24,311 --> 00:18:27,606
Wow. I'm one question away
from being a perfect father.

436
00:18:27,689 --> 00:18:30,484
"Name another dad
you talk to about parenting."

437
00:18:30,567 --> 00:18:31,485
Ohh!

438
00:18:31,568 --> 00:18:32,694
Hey-hey-ho, Simpson.

439
00:18:32,778 --> 00:18:34,988
Shut up, Flanders.
Flanders!

440
00:18:35,072 --> 00:18:37,574
Flanders!
Flanders, uh... uh...

441
00:18:37,658 --> 00:18:40,119
When should a boy start dating?

442
00:18:40,202 --> 00:18:41,995
Well, sir, there are two schools
of thought on the subject...

443
00:18:42,079 --> 00:18:43,455
Great! Thanks.

444
00:18:43,539 --> 00:18:45,499
I talked to Flanders
about parenting!

445
00:18:45,582 --> 00:18:47,626
I'm a perfect father!

446
00:18:47,709 --> 00:18:48,836
Hold on, son.

447
00:18:48,919 --> 00:18:50,003
I'm a-coming.

448
00:18:53,590 --> 00:18:55,425
My friend and I have a bet.

449
00:18:55,509 --> 00:18:58,387
Are you Mary Tyler Moore?

450
00:18:58,470 --> 00:19:00,013
(screaming)

451
00:19:00,097 --> 00:19:01,723
(belches)

452
00:19:01,807 --> 00:19:04,393
Ooh! Wow!
It really is you.

453
00:19:04,476 --> 00:19:06,979
Bart, if she breaks up on you,
steer away from the grandstands

454
00:19:07,062 --> 00:19:10,107
or else you might kill hundreds
of innocent spectators.

455
00:19:10,190 --> 00:19:11,900
Bart, what did I
just tell you?

456
00:19:11,984 --> 00:19:14,611
Kill spectators.

457
00:19:14,695 --> 00:19:16,488
What is the matter
with you?

458
00:19:16,572 --> 00:19:18,615
It's my dad--
lying there on the couch

459
00:19:18,699 --> 00:19:20,617
drinking a beer,
staring at the TV.

460
00:19:20,701 --> 00:19:22,619
I've never seen him
like that.

461
00:19:22,703 --> 00:19:24,538
Forget about your father!

462
00:19:24,621 --> 00:19:25,998
You're driving for me now.

463
00:19:31,378 --> 00:19:34,298
Do it for your old man, boy.

464
00:19:35,632 --> 00:19:37,259
Simpson, prepare to die.

465
00:19:37,342 --> 00:19:38,802
Let's rock.

466
00:19:38,886 --> 00:19:40,804
MAN (on P.A.):
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>

467
00:19:40,888 --> 00:19:43,182
<i>to drop the green flag--</i>
<i>our beloved mayor</i>

468
00:19:43,265 --> 00:19:45,017
Diamond Joe Quimby.

469
00:19:45,100 --> 00:19:49,521
To everyone participating today,
I salute your vigor.

470
00:19:49,605 --> 00:19:51,732
Check out the rack on the blonde
in the fourth row.

471
00:19:55,194 --> 00:19:57,112
(crowd cheering)

472
00:19:57,196 --> 00:19:59,948
MARGE:
Go! Go! Go! Go!

473
00:20:01,450 --> 00:20:03,202
Ha! Ha!

474
00:20:03,285 --> 00:20:05,120
ANNOUNCER:
<i>Like the elegant Roman in Judah Ben Hur,</i>

475
00:20:05,204 --> 00:20:06,788
<i>these modern charioteers</i>
<i>battle ferociously.</i>

476
00:20:06,872 --> 00:20:09,499
<i>No quarter given, none asked.</i>

477
00:20:23,347 --> 00:20:26,099
(camera clicking)

478
00:20:31,021 --> 00:20:33,065
<i>The world has not seen</i>
<i>the likes of this</i>

479
00:20:33,148 --> 00:20:34,858
<i>since the French</i>
<i>carried Lucky Lindy off</i>

480
00:20:34,942 --> 00:20:36,985
<i>on their shoulders,</i>
<i>from Le Bourget Field.</i>

481
00:20:37,069 --> 00:20:38,654
EMCEE:
<i>And now, to present the trophy,</i>

482
00:20:38,737 --> 00:20:42,032
three-time Soap Box Derby
champion, Ronnie Beck.

483
00:20:42,115 --> 00:20:45,077
(applause)

484
00:20:45,160 --> 00:20:46,912
Congratulations, Bart.

485
00:20:46,995 --> 00:20:49,873
Seeing you out there brought
back a lot of memories.

486
00:20:49,957 --> 00:20:51,124
Thanks, Mr. Beck.

